  "motivation": "Currently, Chromium does not support the download attribute on SVG <a> elements (SVGAElement), despite its support in other major browsers such as Firefox. This inconsistency leads to fragmented behavior across platforms and complicates web development workflows, especially for applications relying on SVG-based UI components or graphics that include downloadable resources.\n\nBy implementing this feature, Chromium will:\n\n- Improve interoperability with other browsers (such as Firefox), aligning with the SVG 2 specification.\n- Enhance developer ergonomics by providing consistent behavior across HTML and SVG anchor elements.\n- Support modern web use cases, such as downloadable SVG-based assets and interactive graphics.\n- Reduce the need for workarounds, such as duplicating anchor logic in HTML or using JavaScript to simulate download behavior.\n\nOverall, this change builds on existing anchor element infrastructure and contributes to Chromium’s goal of a more standards-compliant and developer-friendly web platform.",
  "devtrial_instructions": null,
  "activation_risks": null,
  "measurement": null,
  "availability_expectation": null,
  "adoption_expectation": null,
  "adoption_plan": null,
  "initial_public_proposal_url": null,
  "explainer_links": [],
  "requires_embedder_support": false,
  "spec_link": "https://svgwg.org/svg2-draft/linking.html#InterfaceSVGAElement",
  "api_spec": true,
  "automation_spec": false,
  "interop_compat_risks": "\nInteroperability Risk: Low\n\nThe download attribute on SVGAElement is currently supported in Firefox, with no known support in Safari/WebKit or other engines. The implementation is based on a well-defined behavior already supported in HTMLAnchorElement and formalized in the SVG 2 specification.\n\nCompatibility Risk: Very Low\n\nSVG links without the download attribute will continue to behave as they do today. For content that does use the attribute, the behavior will mirror that of HTML anchor elements, minimizing surprises and reducing the learning curve for developers.\n\nOverall, this change is expected to improve interoperability and developer experience with minimal risk to compatibility or stability.",
  "all_platforms": true,
  "all_platforms_descr": null,
  "non_oss_deps": null,
  "anticipated_spec_changes": null,
  "security_risks": null,
  "ergonomics_risks": null,
  "wpt": false,
  "wpt_descr": "While Web Platform Tests (WPT) are not suitable for validating actual file downloads—due to the limitations of sandboxed test environments and the inability to reliably assert file system interactions—we have instead added browser tests to verify the functionality. These browser-level tests simulate user interactions and confirm that the download behavior is correctly triggered and handled by the browser. This approach ensures accurate validation of the feature in a controlled environment, where download flows can be observed and asserted reliably.",
  "webview_risks": null,
  "devrel_emails": [
    "devrel-chromestatus-all@google.com"
  ],
  "debuggability": "The implementation of the download attribute on SVGAElement builds upon Chromium’s existing anchor element infrastructure, ensuring consistent behavior and straightforward debugging. Developers can inspect and interact with the attribute using standard DevTools workflows.",
